[2] USA (Utah): fox
Date: Thu 9 Jun 2022
Source: KUTV [edited]
https://kutv.com/news/local/2-foxes-found-dead-in-salt-lake-county-confirmed-positive-with-bird-flu/


Last month [May 2022], the Utah Division of Wildlife Resources (DWR) identified the 1st case of avian flu in wild birds in Cache County, and now the virus has spread to 2 foxes. A red fox was discovered dead in a homeowner's yard in Murray on 24 May 2022, and another red fox was discovered dead 2 days later in a yard in Taylorsville.

Both were collected by DWR officials and taken to the Utah Veterinary Diagnostic Laboratory in Logan for testing. The samples were then sent to the National Veterinary Services Laboratory in Ames, Iowa, where it was determined that they contained highly pathogenic avian influenza.

Officials with Utah DWR said 25 wild birds in 6 Utah counties had tested positive for the bird flu, including Cache, Weber, Salt Lake, Utah, Tooele, and Carbon. Raptors and waterbirds, specifically Canada geese, great horned owls, hawks, pelicans, turkey vultures, and ducks, are among the birds. The results of other bird deaths are still pending.

"While it does happen, it's not very common for wildlife species other than birds to get highly pathogenic avian influenza," DWR Veterinarian Ginger Stout said. "Some states have had 1 or 2 cases in wild mammals, but it's pretty infrequent, and it seems to affect younger animals more often when it does occur."

The last outbreak of bird flu in the [United] States was reported back in 2014 through 2015. There were 2 ducks detected with the virus during that outbreak.

[Byline: Kayla Winn]

