Communicated by:
ProMED

[Infections of HPAI viruses in mammals are typically not common, but red foxes have shown to be susceptible to infection by HPAI H5N1 and H5N8 previously in Europe and Japan, and there have been many reports since April [2022] in North America. Other carnivores found infected by the Eurasian HPAI H5N1 in America are skunks.

The frequent reports of carnivores infected by HPAI in North America might result from differential exposure (e.g., high quantity of infected birds used as food items by wild carnivores in the Americas compared with Eurasia), or due to mutations that render a viral lineage more capable of infecting carnivores. The fact that there is a high number of reports of HPAI H5N1 in birds of prey and scavengers suggests that predators/scavengers in general (both mammals and birds) are highly exposed. However, virus evolution and adaptive mutations must be closely monitored to rapidly identify viruses with increased potential to infect mammals. - Mod.PMB

